to rest in a warm place for 1 hour. Clean and dry mixing bowl. Meanwhile, continue with boerewors burgers."},{"isHeader":true,"content":"Boerewors Burgers"},{"content":"Place coriander seeds, cloves, ground nutmeg, black peppercorns and sunflower oil in mixing bowl, toast <b>2 min\/120°C\/speed 1<b>, then grind <b>20 sec\/speed 10<b>. Scrape down sides of mixing bowl with spatula."},{"content":"Add beef mince, pork mince and red wine then mix <b>15 sec\/\/speed 4<b>. Transfer to a bowl. With damp hands, shape mixture into 6 burgers, then transfer to a plate, cover and set aside."},{"isHeader":true,"content":"Tomato Sauce, Barbecue Bread and Burgers"},{"content":"Transfer bread dough to a well-floured surface, divide dough into 6 equal pieces then shape into slightly flattened balls. Place on prepared baking tray, cover with a kitchen towel and leave to rise for a further 20 minutes. Meanwhile, continue with recipe."},{"content":"Place onions, parsley and oil in mixing bowl then chop <b>3 sec\/speed 5<b>. Scrape down sides of mixing bowl with spatula then sauté <b>8 min\/120°C\/speed 1<b>."},{"content":"Add chopped tomatoes, black pepper, ½ tsp salt and sugar then cook <b>12 min\/120°C\/speed 1<b>. Meanwhile, preheat barbecue to a low heat."},{"content":"Grease metal grill with oil, place the slightly flattened balls of dough on the grill, cover with aluminium foil and grill for 3-5 minutes. Remove foil, turn roosterkoek over and grill for 3-5 minutes or until they are lightly browned, crispy on the outside and sound hollow when tapped. Season burgers with 1 tsp salt and grill for 3-4 minutes each side, or until cooked as desired. Serve barbecue breads warm with burgers and tomato sauce."}],"hintsAndTricks":["Boerewors is a type of sausage which originated in South Africa, and is very popular in South African cuisine. The name is derived from the Afrikaans words boer (\"farmer\") and wors (\"sausage\"). It can be made with lamb, beef or pork meat, and this version uses a beef-pork meat mixture.<br><br>Roosterkoek, literally translated as \"grill cake\", represents a classic bread to supplement a braai or barbeque. They consist of grilled balls of bread dough and are usually served hot.","The roosterkoek can be cooked in the oven. Preheat oven to 180°C, place on a baking tray lined with baking paper and bake for <b>15-20 minutes.<b>"],"basicInfo":["medium","35m","1h 45m","6 portions"]}